</fr:meta></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>A <fr:em><fr:strong>quasi-inverse</fr:strong></fr:em> to a function <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f \colon  A \to  B]]></fr:tex> is a function <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g \colon  B \to  A]]></fr:tex> equipped with homotopies <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\epsilon \colon  f \circ  g \sim  1_{B}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\eta \colon  g \circ  f \sim 1_{A}]]></fr:tex>, rendering <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g]]></fr:tex> simultaneously a <fr:link
type="local"
href="erct-000Y.xml"
addr="erct-000Y"
title="Section-retraction pair">section</fr:link> and a <fr:link
type="local"
href="erct-000Y.xml"
addr="erct-000Y"
title="Section-retraction pair">retraction</fr:link> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><fr:p>Although no coherence laws are assumed for <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\eta ]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\epsilon ]]></fr:tex>, we shall refer to them respectively as the <fr:em>unit</fr:em> and <fr:em>counit</fr:em> of the quasi-inverse.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
